The package poseid contains different tools. The function merge_prov demonstrate in this vignette provides a method that efficiently generate time series with common spatial definitions over a given time range. To demonstrate this function, we will use the data from the gso package

Installing the poseid and gso packages:

> devtolls::install_github("choisy/poseid")
> devtools::install_github("choisy/gso")

Loading and attaching the poseid and gso packages:

> library(poseid)
> library(gso)

Loading data

For more detail, on how to use the gso package, please look at the vignette Introduction to GSO contains in the gso package. As example, we use the data frame containing the information on the birth and death rate:

> sel <- grep("Crude birth rate, crude death rate and natural increase rate by province", 
+             gso::data_frame_summary$`data frame`)
> data_frame_summary$data_name[sel]

> demo <- demography_8

Merging data

The first utility of this function is to generate appropriate time series. One specificity of Vietnam is the splits of administrative provinces during its history, starting from 40 provinces in 1980 and ending with 63 provinces today, as illustrated below:

We can see that most of the events are splits event of one province into two or three provinces. There is only one merging event of provinces: Ha Noi and Ha Tay in 2008, which merged together to create a new spatial definition of Ha Noi.

The spatial definition of the provinces is changing over time. The different data frames in the gso package contain provinces that are thus defined over various time durations and different spatial units in time.

In order to analyze the data correctly, it is useful to work on time series that cover the same time range and with the same spatial definition through time. The function merge_prov takes care of this by back-merging all the provinces together and returns the data in the same spatial conformation through time.

More information on this function can be find:

> ?merge_prov
Using development documentation for merge_prov

To have a better view of how the function works, we will select only view provinces concerned by some events of spliting or merging. For that, we will need the dplyr package:

> library(dplyr)
> demo <- filter(demo, is.element(province, 
+                 c("Ha Noi", "Hoa Binh", "Ha Tay", "Ha Son Binh", "Dak Lak", "Dak Nong")) == TRUE)
> head(demo)
  province year crude_birth_rate crude_death_rate natural_increase_rate
1  Dak Lak 2005             22.8              5.6                  17.2
2  Dak Lak 2007             21.4              5.4                  16.0
3  Dak Lak 2008             19.6              5.4                  14.2
4  Dak Lak 2009             19.7              5.9                  13.8
5  Dak Lak 2010             19.0              5.8                  13.2
6  Dak Lak 2011             18.4              5.5                  12.9
> unique(demo$province)
[1] "Dak Lak"  "Dak Nong" "Ha Noi"   "Ha Tay"   "Hoa Binh"

For example, if we want to express the area of forest with the province definition of 2000:

> mdemo <- merge_prov(demo, from = "2000-01-01")
> head(mdemo)
# A tibble: 6 x 4

     <chr> <int>                 <chr> <dbl>
1 Dack Lak  2005      crude_birth_rate  49.2

> unique(mdemo$province)

Time range

Automaticaly, the time range selected is from to to = 2017-12-31. But we can change the time-range, we can use the parameters from and to, the only restriction is that the time-range selected overlaps the time range of the data frame inputted.

> mdemo <- merge_prov(demo, from = 1990, to = 2010)
> head(mdemo)
# A tibble: 6 x 4
  province  year                   key value
     <chr> <int>                 <chr> <dbl>
1 Dack Lak  2005      crude_birth_rate  49.2
2 Dack Lak  2005      crude_death_rate  11.5
3 Dack Lak  2005 natural_increase_rate  37.7
4 Dack Lak  2007      crude_birth_rate  45.5
5 Dack Lak  2007      crude_death_rate  11.3
6 Dack Lak  2007 natural_increase_rate  34.2
> unique(mdemo$province)
[1] "Dack Lak" "Ha Noi"  
> range(mdemo$year)
[1] 2005 2010

Functions

By default, the province are merge back together by applying the function sum. We can change this by using the function FUN. For example, here, it can be more interesting here to calculate the mean than the sum when merging back together the provinces.

> merge_prov(demo, from = 1990, to = 2010, FUN = mean)
# A tibble: 30 x 4
   province  year                   key value
      <chr> <int>                 <chr> <dbl>
 1 Dack Lak  2005      crude_birth_rate 24.60
 2 Dack Lak  2005      crude_death_rate  5.75
 3 Dack Lak  2005 natural_increase_rate 18.85
 4 Dack Lak  2007      crude_birth_rate 22.75
 5 Dack Lak  2007      crude_death_rate  5.65
 6 Dack Lak  2007 natural_increase_rate 17.10
 7 Dack Lak  2008      crude_birth_rate 20.90
 8 Dack Lak  2008      crude_death_rate  5.50
 9 Dack Lak  2008 natural_increase_rate 15.40
10 Dack Lak  2009      crude_birth_rate 21.25
# ... with 20 more rows

We can also use weighted mean by providing the weighted in another data frame, for example by the size of the population. For that, we can use the data frame pop_size provides in the gso package. The data been expressed in thousand people, we will change it.

> pop_size <- gso::pop_size
> pop_size <- mutate_if(pop_size, !is.element(names(pop_size), c("province", "year")), funs(1000 * .))
> head(pop_size)
  province year  female    male   rural   total  urban
1 An Giang 1995 1003400  966700 1602100 1970100 368000
2 An Giang 1996 1012600  978100 1619800 1990700 370900
3 An Giang 1997 1022000  989100 1616000 2011100 395100
4 An Giang 1998 1031400 1001100 1634500 2032500 398000
5 An Giang 1999 1043900 1011500 1650100 2055400 405300
6 An Giang 2000 1047600 1014100 1604200 2061700 457500

We can now used the pop_size information in the function with the parameters df2 and args to calculate the weighted mean by the total size of the population. The parameter df2 take data frame as entry and the parameters args should indicate the name of the column containing the weight we want to apply on the data. The parameters df and df2 should have at least one column in commun to be able to join them together.

> merge_prov(demo, from = 1990, FUN = weighted.mean, df2 = pop_size, args = "total")
# A tibble: 60 x 4
   province  year                   key     value
      <chr> <int>                 <chr>     <dbl>
 1 Dack Lak  2005      crude_birth_rate 23.532414
 2 Dack Lak  2005      crude_death_rate  5.661035
 3 Dack Lak  2005 natural_increase_rate 17.871380
 4 Dack Lak  2007      crude_birth_rate 21.973244

Linked to gdpm

It can be interesting to link the epidemiological data from the gdpm package with the informations from the gso package.

In the gdpm package, for two diseases: hepatitis and amoebiasis, the story of splits/combined provinces are different, the events of 1990 take place in 1991. For more information:

> devtools::install_github("choisy/gdpm", build_vignettes = TRUE) # to install the gdpm package
> vignette(package = "gdpm")
> library(gdpm)
> ?getid
> hepatitis <- getid(hepatitis, from = 1990, to = 2017)
Warning in getid_(disease, vect, from = from, to = to): The argument "to" is out of the time range for this
        (these) disease(s): 1980-2015. The closest time range was selected:
        1990-2015.

So, if we want to link the data frame to be express with the same province as the hepatitis or amoebiasis data frame, we can use the parameter diseases.

> demo <- demography_8
> mdemo <- merge_prov(demo, sel = "crude_birth_rate", from = 1990, FUN = weighted.mean,
+                     df2 = pop_size, args = "total") 
> unique(mdemo$province)

[10] "Dong Thap"           "Gia Lai - Kon Tum"   "Ha Bac"
